Clarence Thomas describes his grandfather who raised him as a sort of living myth. Went to a one-room school for three months to third grade. Lost a finger working on a lumber boat. His job was literally just chopping wood at night and then driving around with a truck selling it.

Built a house out of cinder blocks together with his grandsons. Never stopped working from sunrise to sunset and refused to use electrical power tools, just kept himself occupied with hard work all the time, putting up fences, digging wells, fixing his truck. Endearing depiction.

Really reminds me of my own grandfather, who was unable to finish high school because he had to work to feed his family, built our house mostly himself, worked as a truck driver, had missing fingers from metalworking, found work around the yard every day. Old school type of man.

If he's still alive you should ask to record him on video telling his stories, for your own children to watch one day, one of my regrets is I didn't get to do this with mine before he passed away because I was too young to think about that stuff
